,Recommended,253940,11164943,"Posted: 10 July, 2014",all,Lazzie~,"Final Fantasy, toned down in terms of length, and turned into 3D (in comparison to like, FF 1,2, and sorts). Gameplay-wise, you know little of what to do unless some characters explicitly specify you where to go, but fortunately the areas aren't as extensive and misleading as FF's are, so catching up to where you left at will be relatively easy.Combat goes as follows: you can have up to 3 characters at any one time following you, each with different stats, play-style, and skills. When you're in combat, there is a bar under each of your characters that fills up as time goes on, with 2 3-digits numbers that represent your HP. The bar is divided into 3 parts; simply put, if you let it fill in one part, you can only use the basic weapons/moves which deals less damage, but if you let it fill up entirely, you can use more damaging moves (and the same goes for using cards, this game's equivalent of magic). You click on a character's frame when at least one bar is filled up, select the move you want to use (or use items, or invoke card powers), and target the enemy. There is a big bar of blue on top of the combat interface; that's your core energy, or what you'd call Mana, MP, SP, or whatever. NOTHING in combat regenerates, even post-battle (unless you manually use items or rest to recover those combat stats), so keep in mind when you do anything mid battle. The game is generous enough to tell you that when you use a certain move or card, the energy bar shows how much energy that move/card is going to use up, so you can plan your moves carefully. Overall, the combat feels balanced; challenging if you rush through the game with zero grinding, and rewarding if you decide to grind in one area.However, the game does not tell you what any of your character's stats do, so you pretty much have to experiment with each, or deduce yourself what each does. Also, despite the game telling you where to go next explicitly through well-voiced NPC dialogues, it does not tell you what to do when you're in said location.The plot is quite linear, with little, but appreciable amount of side-missions. The lore is, personally, rather extensive for a game that has no sequel. You go from place A to place B, go to C, then back to A for some quick stuffs, and move on to D.Laziness overtook me. I'll just say that if you're someone who enjoys FF or JRPG in general, puzzles, and exploring, this game is worth the price.P.S. get the official patch for this game, otherwise it's unplayable for Windows 7 and above. I wouldn't recommend installing the unofficial patch because it made the game run on like, 2 or 3 fps."
76561198002808530,Recommended,253940,11451503,"Posted: 28 July, 2014",all,Sorlian,"Only played a little bit, but has me feeling nostalgic for FF7, yet somehow reminds me of first two fallouts. This is likely because of the menu setups, and the battles take place in the field (no cutscene). This game is not turned based though, and there is a distinct lack of directions when it comes to controls, though some of it is talked about in dialogue. (Hint: double click and hold to run)"
