,Not Recommended,253940,12089098,"Posted: 13 September, 2014",all,*belch*,"EDIT 4 Oct 2014: I've had some more time to play so I have some new insight. First off, you will NEED a walkthrough. The game does give you precisely zero direction on where your objectives actually are. Second, combat is a CHORE. I find myself dumping as many bonuses as I can into my speed stats just so I can get through it quicker. To be clear, an attack is carried out usually by a combatant jumping toward their attack target, performing their attack animation, then jumping back into their position. This whole time, the entire ATB system stops so you can watch. Combat is structured much like Final Fantasy 13's combat, except far less fluid. You get three action bars, but only one action a turn, and any action you take drains your entire ATB meter. I learned this the hard way. The one thing it does have going for it is that its story is keeping me interested (I do enjoy a good story well told), but combat is going to have to start getting much quicker.------This game is fine but not perfect. I picked it up on sale for a whopping 75 cents and at that price, sure, worth every penny. But then, so are most games.I've been playing it for a little while, but it gives you no instruction on how to play it at all. Opening cutscenes finish and you're just standing there like a dunce.The game is controlled by click-and-holding where you want to go (you can use arrow keys, but...just use the mouse), and your first objective is to get to class.This is me, right now, on that first objective:http://youtu.be/7hR34OGe30I?t=2m14sAt 75 cents, it's a steal. At five bucks...give it some thought."
