76561198008397882,Recommended,253940,33291503,Posted: 5 July,all,yula568,"This game was one of the first games in my life, but only now can I understand, most of it... and I didn't realized how deep and serious this story was. Septerra is masterfully crafted, full of living characters with motivations, fears, and heart. It's a steam-punk-fantasy story about conquest, betrayal, friendship and true humanity. Showing, that the evil doesn't necceseraly must be a demon or monster, because greedy, powerhungry humans can become more dangerous monsters.The actual gameplay is a bit slow. The worst thing in it are the dungeons, what later become a bit confusing mazes. If your sense of direction isn't good, you can become frustrated by loosing your way.I didn't experienced any issues on Windows 10. It's a good port. I just downloaded the game and played immediately perfectly. The graphics are aged, but if you are the fan of retro-games, and doesn't mind some pixels for a good tale, you should play this. There are dozens of new retro-graphic games out there. Why should a realy old, but good game stay behind them?I would realy want to see a remaster of this game.Or a sequel.Or an anime :D"
,Recommended,253940,34100756,Posted: 8 August,all,Arkas,"This is one of the classic RPG games.The female protagonist Maya and her assembled ragtag crew have to save the world!It is heavily influenced by Final Fantasy VII. Turn based combat, summoning mighty beasts, magic and more.It is partially voiced and the graphics are very detailed and still gorgeous to look at.The Story is okay and the characters are relatable.Three big negatives stand out in this game:- The combat becomes boring and monotonous very quickly.- It is not always clear what you need to do and you can get stuck easily without the occasional glance at a Walkthrough-Tutorial.- The level design is nearly always ""Find a lever/key, which opens a previously closed door, while fighting through the same monsters over and over again"". When you finish the boss at the end of the level you...walk all the way back out, fighting through the same monsters again, who have respawned if you had to go through a loading screen.The last point makes this game more drawn out than it had to be - it took me about 55 hours to complete it.While it is nowhere near on Final Fantasy VII's level it was still a pleasure to have finally completed it after all these years."
76561198370109488,Recommended,253940,34571736,Posted: 29 August,all,littlesilvermaiden,"It's older, so the graphics take some getting used to. I played it in middle school, but for some reason the game kept freezing on one specific boss fight. I'm glad I was able to find such an old and little mentioned game here. It's fun, makes you think as you explore and solve puzzles while trying to save the world core."
,Recommended,253940,35066564,Posted: 19 September,all,Tsurayu,"Having played this game many years ago, not long after it first came out, I can't deny that nostalgia might be a heavy influence on my perception of this game.That said, Septerra Core is enjoyable. The story, while not a unique experience, does it's job to motivate the characters and the world around you to action. Big bad scary guy who thinks he is the savior of the world, actually seeks to destroy it and rebuild it in his own divine image, yadda, yadda. Point is, if you've played a few RPGs, you've ran through this story before.What is unique, perhaps for better or for worse depending on your tastes, is the gameplay. It's a derivative of the ATB system found in a lot of earlier JRPGs. The pacing is admittedly very slow. Don't expect most battles, regardless of your level or equipment to take any less than a minute to complete. While the game wants to appear to appear and play like a JRPG (mind you this is an entirely American CRPG) its Western side shines through in it's difficulty. The game is punishing, and never really relents. You can grind, and grind, and grind. But at the end of the day, your wits will have to be about you. Sure, you can cheese a lot of encounters with FATE cards (think games magic system) but you are limited in how many times you can use them before restoring your Core (think a shared MP pool between party members).Presentation is what you would come to expect from a lot of Western RPGs of the late 90s. Developers really seemed to love their FMVs, which I should note as of the most recent patch, should play without any need for you to mess with the dreaded Quicktime. The music is definitely one of the weakpoints. I wouldn't say it's terrible, or will make your ears bleed. However, there isn't a single song, tune or sound effect that will be memerable, and perhaps more than a few that might actually annoy you (particularly with some commonly reused sound effects).The real highlight for the game, at least in my eyes, is the attention the developers game to making this Western RPG feel  and play similarly to a JRPG. Remember that in the late 90s JRPGs still weren't really ""clicking"" overseas. Sure, the Final Fantasy games had started to become a bit of a household name at this time thanks to FFVII, but there were still a lot of WRPG players that weren't willing to adapt to the more thematic style of their Japanese counterparts. This game, while certianly not the only title, went a lot way to helping to bridge that gap. While Septerra Core might end up as more of a historical footnote in that regard, it is an overall fun and challenging RPG whose deficits are outweighed by it's uniqueness."
